  "prompt": "Programming Languages: What was the first REPL?",
  "response": "The first REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) is generally attributed to the Lisp programming language, specifically in the implementation by Steve Russell at MIT in the early 1960s, working under John McCarthy (Lisp's creator).\n\nIn the Lisp interpreter, Russell implemented an interactive environment where:\n- Read: Input was read from the user\n- Eval: The input was evaluated/executed\n- Print: The result was printed back to the user\n- Loop: The process would repeat, allowing continuous interaction\n\nThis interactive programming environment was groundbreaking at the time, as most programming was done through batch processing, where code was submitted and results returned later. The Lisp REPL allowed programmers to experiment and get immediate feedback.\n\nWhile some argue that earlier interactive systems might have existed, the Lisp REPL is widely recognized as the first mature, general-purpose REPL in programming language history.\n\nToday, REPLs are common in many languages like Python, Ruby, JavaScript (Node.js), Haskell, and others, but Lisp pioneered the concept.",
